#Text=4 --
#Text=The Halt on the Turnpike Road
#Text=Down , downward they went , and yet further down -- their descent at each step seeming to outmeasure their advance .

#Text=Their skirts were scratched noisily by the furze , their shoulders brushed by the ferns , which , though dead and dry , stood erect as when alive , no sufficient winter weather having as yet arrived to beat them down .
#Text=Their Tartarean situation might by some have been called an imprudent one for two unattended women .
#Text=But these shaggy recesses were at all seasons a familiar surrounding to Olly and Mrs. Yeobright ; and the addition of darkness lends no frightfulness to the face of a friend .
#Text=“ And so Tamsin has married him at last , ” said Olly , when the incline had become so much less steep that their foot-steps no longer required undivided attention .
#Text=Mrs. Yeobright answered slowly , “ Yes ; at last . ”
#Text=“ How you will miss her -- living with ' ee as a daughter , as she always have . ”
#Text=“ I do miss her . ”
#Text=Olly , though without the tact to perceive when remarks were untimely , was saved by her very simplicity from rendering them offensive .
#Text=Questions that would have been resented in others she could ask with impunity .
#Text=This accounted for Mrs. Yeobright 's acquiescence in the revival of an evidently sore subject .
#Text=“ I was quite strook to hear you 'd agreed to it , ma'am , that I was , ” continued the besom-maker .
#Text=“ You were not more struck by it than I should have been last year this time , Olly .
#Text=There are a good many sides to that wedding .
#Text=I could not tell you all of them , even if I tried . ”
#Text=“ I felt myself that he was hardly solid-going enough to mate with your family .
#Text=Keeping an inn -- what is it ? But ' a 's clever , that 's true , and they say he was an engineering gentleman once , but has come down by being too outwardly given . ”
#Text=“ I saw that , upon the whole , it would be better she should marry where she wished . ”
#Text=“ Poor little thing , her feelings got the better of her , no doubt . ' Tis nature .
#Text=Well , they may call him what they will -- he 've several acres of heth-ground broke up here , besides the public house , and the heth-croppers , and his manners be quite like a gentleman 's .
#Text=And what 's done cannot be undone . ”
#Text=“ It cannot , ” said Mrs. Yeobright .
#Text=“ See , here 's the wagon-track at last .
#Text=Now we shall get along better . ”

#Text=The wedding subject was no further dwelt upon ; and soon a faint diverging path was reached , where they parted company , Olly first begging her companion to remind Mr. Wildeve that he had not sent her sick husband the bottle of wine promised on the occasion of his marriage .

#Text=The besom-maker turned to the left towards her own house , behind a spur of the hill , and Mrs. Yeobright followed the straight track , which further on joined the highway by the Quiet Woman Inn , whither she supposed her niece to have returned with Wildeve from their wedding at Anglebury that day .
#Text=She first reached Wildeve 's Patch , as it was called , a plot of land redeemed from the heath , and after long and laborious years brought into cultivation .
#Text=The man who had discovered that it could be tilled died of the labour ; the man who succeeded him in possession ruined himself in fertilizing it .
#Text=Wildeve came like Amerigo Vespucci , and received the honours due to those who had gone before .

#Text=When Mrs. Yeobright had drawn near to the inn , and was about to enter , she saw a horse and vehicle some two hundred yards beyond it , coming towards her , a man walking alongside with a lantern in his hand .
#Text=It was soon evident that this was the reddleman who had inquired for her .
#Text=Instead of entering the inn at once , she walked by it and towards the van .

#Text=The conveyance came close , and the man was about to pass her with little notice , when she turned to him and said , “ I think you have been inquiring for me ? I am Mrs. Yeobright of Blooms-End . ”
#Text=The reddleman started , and held up his finger .
#Text=He stopped the horses , and beckoned to her to withdraw with him a few yards aside , which she did , wondering .
#Text=“ You do n't know me , ma'am , I suppose ? ” he said .
#Text=“ I do not , ” said she .
#Text=“ Why , yes , I do ! You are young Venn -- your father was a dairyman somewhere here ? ”
#Text=“ Yes ; and I knew your niece , Miss Tamsin , a little .
#Text=I have something bad to tell you . ”
#Text=“ About her -- no ! She has just come home , I believe , with her husband .
#Text=They arranged to return this afternoon -- to the inn beyond here . ”
#Text=“ She 's not there . ”
#Text=“ How do you know ? ”
#Text=“ Because she 's here .
#Text=She 's in my van , ” he added slowly .
#Text=“ What new trouble has come ? ” murmured Mrs. Yeobright , putting her hand over her eyes .
#Text=“ I ca n't explain much , ma'am .

#Text=All I know is that , as I was going along the road this morning , about a mile out of Anglebury , I heard something trotting after me like a doe , and looking round there she was , white as death itself .
#Text=' Oh , Diggory Venn ! ' she said , ' I thought ' twas you -- will you help me ?
#Text=I am in trouble . ' ”
#Text=“ How did she know your Christian name ? ” said Mrs. Yeobright doubtingly .
#Text=“ I had met her as a lad before I went away in this trade .
#Text=She asked then if she might ride , and then down she fell in a faint .
#Text=I picked her up and put her in , and there she has been ever since .
#Text=She has cried a good deal , but she has hardly spoke ; all she has told me being that she was to have been married this morning .
#Text=I tried to get her to eat something , but she could n't ; and at last she fell asleep . ”
